        "body": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "In New York City, COVID-19 cases are rising, with the city’s positivity rate at 4.53%, and a reported 127 deaths in the past 7 days.  As seen across the country, working class people of color have faced the brunt of the pandemic, from health vulnerability and deaths to unemployment."
          },
          {
            "type": "graphic",
            "value": {
              "asset": "covid-chart.html",
              "steps": [
                "In the zipcode that Morningside Heights and Columbia occupies (10027), the positivity rate is 2.41% as of December 2nd.",
                "For West Harlem residents in the 10031 zipcode, the positivity rate is more than twice that at 5.19%.",
                "On Columbia’s campus, the positivity rate is 0.29%, just a fraction of that in the broader area."
              ]
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "The low positivity rates on campus can in part be traced to Columbia’s rigorous testing program, in which all university affiliates who frequent the campus are required to undergo weekly testing. Erick Zent CC ‘24 and first-year class president, says the testing is very accessible for Columbia affiliates who wish to utilize it."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“It’s actually really easy to get the test,” Zent said. “All you have to do is go to the Columbia University Health corner portal and then make an appointment.”"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Zent, who is currently on campus, said that it is a mixture of the weekly testing and the “stringent” enforcement of rules laid out in the Columbia Community Health Compact that have accounted for this low positivity rate."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "<a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/news/2020/07/28/columbia-asked-students-to-pledge-to-ensure-a-campus-safe-from-covid-19-not-everyone-is-on-board/\"><i>[Related: Columbia asked students to pledge to ensure a campus safe from COVID-19. Not everyone is on board</i></a><i>]</i>"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "While this is good news for Columbia, a far different story exists outside the University’s gates for West Harlem residents."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Elsia Vasquez, the founder of tenants right advocacy group P.A.’L.A.N.T.E. Harlem, describes her client make up as “majority Black and Brown”, and noted that they seemed to face the brunt of the pandemic."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“I would say that 50 to 55% of our clients have contracted the virus,” Vasquez said. “Thank God most of them have survived, but the double down and triple down in one apartment being incurred upon definitely has an impact.”"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Edwin Torres, a co-chair of the Health and Environment committee on Community Board 9 and a nurse practitioner at Montefiore Medical Center, believes the high COVID-19 rates in West Harlem zip codes are due in large part to a lack of access to community resources for testing."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“What I hear in the community is that we need more testing centers,” Torres said. “We need a testing center to be here in the community, and we’re working with the Health Department to see how we can create spaces that can be more accessible for the community.”"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "There are multiple hospitals in the surrounding area that makes up CB9, including Mount Sinai and CUMC/New York-Presbyterian hospital. However, despite the hospitals’ presence in the area, residents are still wary of going to the hospitals, as they recall the state of disarray that took place when the virus first hit in early spring this year."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“We know that hospitals are doing a great job at providing some of these resources but we also need to understand the fear that the community has,” Torres said. “If you build it, and they don't come then you build it for nothing.”"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "As such, to accommodate for the community’s skepticism towards hospitals at the moment, other CB9 members have monthly meetings with the Department of Health and continue to push for more resources directly in the community."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“Hospitals that have done a terrific job implementing protocols to make sure that their ERs are safe and that their facilities are safe,” Torres said. “But the population doesn't want to go there. So we need to make sure we come to the population.”"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "He described the popularity of the City MD located on 146th and Broadway as an example of the efficacy of in-community testing centers."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“There's a huge line every day,” Torres said. “People prefer to go to places like that because they just feel that this is a safer place than attending a hospital.”"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "However, these community testing sites are rare in the West Harlem area. There are currently no community testing centers in the 10031 zip code, despite the fact that its positivity rate is greater than 5%."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“We absolutely do need a testing center in the community,” Torres said."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Research has shown that the high positivity rates directly correlate with areas with high populations of low-income residents, as well as lower rates of testing. Wil Lieberman-Cribbin, a first-year doctoral student in Environmental Health Sciences at Columbia and the Melman School of Public Health, analyzed data from the New York State Department of Health from the first recorded month of the pandemic and noted the disparities in testing along racial and socioeconomic lines."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“We were really interested in investigating if testing was performed in areas that were proportional to need,” Lieberman-Cribbin said."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Lieberman-Cribbin’s research team studied the distribution of testing and positive test results across 177 zip code tabulation areas. They then calculated a Socioeconomic Score (SES), which he described as a “weighted measure of multiple variables such as household income, rent amount, whether the population lives in apartments, education, unemployment, and crowdedness of area” along with other factors."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“The main result of what we found is that more tests were performed in areas with an increasingly white racial composition,” Lieberman-Cribbin said. “And then conversely, areas that had the highest proportion of positive tests were in mostly non-white neighborhoods and in areas that had a lower SES, so that that was the main result.”"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Residents in neighborhoods with higher SES scores were more likely to go get tested as a preventative, or screening measure. Those in neighborhoods with lower scores were more likely to use testing as a diagnostic tool. Lieberman-Cribbin points to a range of reasons for this disparity in testing."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“There's the issue of costs,” Lieberman-Cribbin said. “And there's the issue of proximity, and then health literacy, and then access and time.”"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "While his initial research may have only been centered around the recorded data from March 2nd to April 6th, Lieberman-Cribbin’s team is still noticing a disproportionate lack of testing in low-SES areas."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“We still found that there were more tests regardless in more well off areas like Manhattan compared to Central queens and that the opposite was true for positive results,” Lieberman-Cribbin said."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "As local residents bear the brunt of the city’, community organizations have stepped in to help residents have the resources they need to protect themselves. Although PA'LANTE has historically been centered around tenant advocacy, Vasquez’s organization adjusted once COVID-19 hit in order to best support the communities they serve.This has meant opening the office 7 days a week, and adding services that provide much-needed PPE for tenants in all different boroughs."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Vasquez described a story of a woman in the Bronx whose husband passed away because he could not wear a mask at work, as well as people lining up for their Thanksgiving turkey drives with visibility dirty masks because they could not afford to purchase duplicates."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“Getting those guys PPE, that’s what’s important for us right now,” Vasquez said."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "Her service in providing masks and hand sanitizer for this population has led her to working with the mayor and governor’s office to gather more resources, as well as the tenants themselves in the community to distribute the resources directly to residents."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“We have a lot of tenants’ associations in Morningside Heights and West Harlem,” Vasquez said. “ {For} the tenants’ organizations that we’ve already built in the community, we get the leaders involved, and when it comes to the different buildings that we know are in the community we just go there.”"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "However, Vasquez feels that there is still much more work to do to help community members through this pandemic."
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "“I know that more can be done simply because the numbers continue to grow,” Vasquez said. People continue to get sick.”"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "value": "<i>Staff writer Faith Andrews can be contacted at </i><i>faith.andrews@columbiaspectator.com</i><i>. Follow Spectator on Twitter at </i><a href=\"https://twitter.com/ColumbiaSpec?ref_src=twsrc%5Egoogle%7Ctwcamp%5Eserp%7Ctwgr%5Eauthor\"><i>@ColumbiaSpec</i></a><i>.</i>"
          }
        ],
        "headline": "As the pandemic worsens, West Harlem residents struggle with higher COVID-19 rates and a lack of accessible testing",
        "date": "December 13, 2020",
